segments.text: We're in the beautiful home this afternoon of Dr. Dan Anderson of Fulton City, that's Fort Worth, Texas, an illustrious veterinarian who can look back on a very long and productive career.
I think we ought to start with his background, tell where he was born and brought up, and I think we ought to start a little bit with his parents.
Dan, tell us about your mother and father, when they were born and what their names were.
Well, my mother's name
was McCoskey, Lucille McCoskey, and that couldn't be anything but Irish, you know.
My father was William L. Anderson, and his parents were natives of Rockwell.
My great-grandfather
father on that side.
You say your daddy's parents were natives of Rockwell, Texas?
Yes.
Boy, that goes back a long ways.
Over 100 years.
And my great-grandfather migrated to this country.
We have those old letters to show.
But before the Civil War, of course.
And came out of southern Indiana.
Uniontown, Indiana, and I thought I'd go back up there and look around.
Just one of those things I haven't done.
That's close to Lincoln country.
Yes, yes.
Sure is.
Yeah.
Not too far.
But anyway, my background is from a stock farm.
My mother and father...
reared four children, two girls and two boys.
And you were brought up in Rockwall?
East of Rockwall, on the stock farm.
And my parents weren't, they always had to work to educate the kids, but
I think they did a tremendous job because all four of us got an education.
What type of schoolhouse did you go to?
You started out in first grade?
Rockwell?
I lived so far out in the country that we couldn't commute in that black land over there.
The first two years I was in school,
I stayed with my grandparents, my Anderson grandparents in Rockwall, and went to school.
And then in the third grade, I went to Royce City, which was five miles from my home.
By that time, old Paul Ferguson had built some little concrete highways that we could get to town on out of that black land, so the kids

the three of us the older ones started to royce city you were a ferguson fan were you oh uh everybody voted for jim ferguson out there in that agricultural country and anybody that didn't vote for him well they ran them off they wouldn't they wouldn't lease land to them the next year but anyway uh uh we spent uh

two years we went to Royce City then we transferred back to Rockwell which was kind of home base for us always and most of the family both sides of the family lived there and I graduated from from Rockwell High School in 1934.
You didn't have the honor of going to a one-room grade school did you?
No.
That was too bad.
I was
I was fortunate or unfortunate enough to have to go to a larger school.
Then I had dreams of athletics and had an opportunity to go to Texas Tech when the old coach that was out there came by and
talked to Charles Atkins and I.
And I went out and looked around.
And then between the time I talked with him and September, it was back during the Depression there.
And we had an assistant county agent come into Rockwell County that somehow convinced me that I ought to go to A&M.
You're talking about 1933?
No, about 1934, the summer of 34.
And I went to A&M and the first year I studied animal science or animal husbandry back there then and minored in business.
And at the end of my freshman year, I decided that veterinary medicine was the best animal husbandry course I could take.
So I transferred over to the School of Veterinary Medicine and went to summer school after my freshman year and got government, freshman physiology, and organic chemistry behind me.
I gathered up the courses as best I could and graduated with my class.
I guess you'd say I'm just a three-year student, because I went to that summer school.
But then I didn't know until the last term of my senior year whether I was going to graduate.
I didn't know whether I'd get my courses in or not.
But back there then, I took freshman
anatomy and sophomore anatomy together.
Of course, I went to school day and night, you know, around the clock.
That was 1936, your freshman anatomy.
Mark Francis was still around then, wasn't he?
Oh, yes.
Let me see.
In 1935 and 1936, I studied anatomy under Dr. Francis.
He had an assistant that taught us
that taught also, but Dr. Francis was head of the department, of course.
And then there was Marsteller, Dr. Marsteller.
These two gentlemen had rather different personalities, didn't they?
What was Dr. Francis like?
Oh, Dr. Francis was just a staid gentleman.
as far as the students were concerned.
He couldn't hear.
If you wanted to talk to him, you had to write something down.
He said, that didn't make any difference.
Most of what you hear is not worth a darn anyway.
He didn't let that deter him because he had no hearing.
But he was very capable and
And he always had some little way of tying that anatomical structure or that artery and nerve or that bone.
He'd tie it to something that you'd see in the clinic some of these days.
I remember he was no doubt talking about the stifle.
And he showed us how a string-halted horse would walk, see?
And he says, you'll find it right there.
You'll know all about that, though, when you get to talking to Marsteller down there in the clinic.
And he just had a way of impressing you with those important structures, that part of the anatomy which he felt that you'd be using the most.
or it'd kind of be everyday use for you when you got out and got into practice.
Mark Steller was a very peculiar individual.
I always got along well with him.
But some of the students, if they
If they did something that Mark Stoller didn't like, well, he had a way of making things rough on them.
But I always got along fine with the old man.
Never had a bit of trouble with him.
In fact, I, of course, used a little politics.
I didn't realize I was doing it at the time.
When I transferred from animal husbandry over to the School of Veterinary Medicine, I had some electives that I could take.
I had a year of college math, and I had a year of agronomy, and I had some agroeconomics.
I could use as electives.
There were a certain number of elective subjects in the last two years of veterinary medicine.
And I needed those electives.
And I went down to see him one day, first of my sophomore year.
And, well, he said, Mr. Anderson, you don't need any mathematics in veterinary medicine.
That agricultural economics, you can just throw that out the window and says,
Lord, that agronomy.
I don't see where we can take any of that as electives.
I said, well, all right, sir.
So I thought, well, if I don't get something done, I'm going to be in this institution an extra year.
But the following fall, my junior year, we were in clinic in that old amphitheater down there.
Marsteller walked in that Saturday morning.
He says, now, gentlemen, we're having a football game over here today.
Baylor University is coming over here, and we're having all of the legislatures coming over here from Austin.
They got on a special train and came over, all the legislatures.
Well, I got to think, and it says, if you know a representative or if you know a state senator, be nice to him because that's where our money comes from.
Well, I got to thinking about it.
I had politicked for my state senator.
I'd stumped for him.
And I wanted him to meet Marsteller.
I said, you know, I don't know what I was thinking back then, but anyway.
Soon as that football game was over, I had Claude Isabel spotted, and I found Marsteller, and I got them together.
I said, this is Senator Isabel.
Oh, yeah, Doctor.
And Isabel was an influential man in Austin at that time.
So Marsteller put us in that old Studebaker sedan of his, took us down to the hospital, and opened the door, and says, show him around, Dan.
And I showed him around, you know, and I forget now what all we went into.
But anyway, then we took the senator back and put him on the train.
The old man gave me one of those Maxauer cigars and took me around to the dormitory.
And he was just pleased as punch, you know.
And, of course, I was happy that we got them together.
But anyway...
I went on to the house, but on Monday afternoon, as soon as I got a chance, I went down to see Marsteller.
Come in, Dan.
What can I do for you?
Well, I've got some courses here I want to transfer as electives.
I've got some college math here.
Oh, yeah, everybody, that's basic.
Everybody ought to have mathematics.
Everybody ought to have some mathematics, that algebra especially.
And that

agricultural economics says that that just gives you a more well-rounded education and that agronomy you know that's that that's the earth that you everybody ought to have that too and i said well now that's what what else i said that's all that's all that's all i have yeah well couldn't we couldn't we use that in place of something else no sure i said that's all well that was that was 12 hours
Let me see.
I think Bull Tech's advanced military science was a three-hour course.
So that was six hours in junior year and six hours in the senior year, as well as I remember.
So it was 12 hours of work, and he just flipped it over to me just like that.
Well, anyway, Mark Steller had his faults, but again, I remember
when I had finished school, and I hadn't been out of school very long, and... You graduated in... 1938, yes.
Go ahead.
I needed a recommendation.
I was going to work for the Ralston Purina Company, and they wanted a letter of recommendation from the school and my credits and all that stuff.
And he wrote me the darndest recommendation ever.
Well, he did that for all of the boys.
After they got out, if he could do anything for them.
Now, he was hard on Dick.
He was hard on Dick.
And he was hard on several of the older of the students above me.
Dick who?
Dick Self?
Oh, Dick.
Dickinson.
Dickinson.
Ray Dickinson.
Oh, yeah.
OK. All right.
All right.
But I got along fine with Marsteller and Dr. Leonard.
We were fortunate back there then to have the professors down there that we had.

I give them a lot of credit for... Up until that time, the School of Veterinary Medicine, as far as legislative acts for funds, it was very difficult for the veterinary division to get very much funding.
Isn't that right?
Oh, that's right.
And your class was small.
Isn't that correct, too?
The class before me, I think, had eight or ten students.
But my class comes along, and we had about 32, I think, or 35, or something like that.
But the financing was a per capita thing, based on the number of students that you had.
And that's why after 38, or after my class graduated, we had a lot of those boys from New York, and New Jersey, and all over the world that
came in here and they were accepted.
But it was a necessity to keep the school going.
When you graduated, did you work for Ralston Purina to start?
Well, no.
I spent my junior, the summer of my junior year, in San Antonio with Drs.
Gleeson and Neal.
And that was the best three months of training that I had prior to graduation.
It was a mixed practice?
In a mixed practice.
And after spending one summer down there with them, I went back to A&M, and if there was a surgery to do, I'd grab it and do it.
You know, those other boys were...

they were a little hesitant because they hadn't had that hands-on training like i had then i went back with them for uh two or three months after i graduated and this opportunity with ralston purina came up and i went with them for a couple of years that brought you up to 1940 and the war was beginning uh well i i moved back to uh back to taro texas which is

only about 15 miles from my old home and uh went into practice there i was there for uh well i was with uh i was with Purina only a year i guess and then i came back there and i was in practice two years until august of 1941 and i was called into active beauty
old General McCallum, it was Colonel McCallum then, was service command veterinarian, 8th service command veterinarian.
And he was stationed in San Antonio.
I reported into Fort Sam Houston August the 13th, 1941.
And I had been there about
two weeks.
And they had the maneuvers going on in Louisiana.
25,000 men down in Louisiana, the biggest maneuver they'd had since World War I.
And they needed a little help up here on meat procurement in Fort Worth.
So McCallum told me, he said, uh,
We are going to send you to Fort Worth for about 30 days, and then I'll bring you back here, and I'll send you to Chicago to the meat school.
Then I'll give you an airfield out here somewhere to handle.
I said, that's all right.
That's fine.
Well, I'd been up here about 30 days, and I was with Colonel Ludwigs.
Colonel Ludwigs called me in one day and says, how would you like to stay here?
Well, I said, Colonel, that'd make me so darn mad I wouldn't know what to do.
He said, well, we're going to keep you.
So I fought the war right here in Dallas and Fort Worth.
I was head of procurement in Dallas for a year or two.
But our group weren't moved because
At the outbreak of war, we were shown, our 201 files showed that we were at the San Antonio QM Depot.
Then in a year or two, when the Fort Worth Quartermaster Depot was formed, we showed to have transferred from San Antonio to Fort Worth.
Well, during the war, you know, they tried to transfer you around.
If you'd been to a place so long, you know, they'd transfer you to some other place.
And because we, our 201 file showed that we had had a transfer, we just fought the war right here in Fort Worth.
However, there was quite a bit to be done.
The Fort Worth stockyards were in their heyday in those days.
And there was a lot of procurement going on, and the Veterinary Corps at that time really got a pretty good name for itself in the inspection and procurement situation.
Isn't that correct?
Really and truly, the Veterinary Corps did a tremendous job.
Tell us about your operation here in Fort Worth with the Quartermaster.
We had, I guess, eight or 10 veterinary officers permanently assigned here.
And then on into the war, we had a schooling.
What did they call it?
Well, anyway, we brought young veterinary officers in that
And they were assigned to us on temporary duty until they either went to Chicago or were transferred out somewhere else.
And we were charged with the responsibility of seeing that these contracts were filled with the product as designated in the contract.
that the product met those specifications.
And we pretty well, as far as the sanitation and all, we had the help of the USDA people.
But there were times when we had to blow the whistle because of sanitary reasons, not
Necessarily at the packing house, but at some other places that we had around here that were producing food products.
But anyway, we had Armor and Swift, and we had procurement from the Fort Worth Poultry and Egg Company and one or two other poultry places.
And then we had dairy products.
We even bought fish.
Fish.
And it got to the point there at one time where we bought carp from McQuillan's Fish Market, I think it was.
But I even did inspection.
They sent me to Dallas.
I hadn't been in service too long to inspect a canning plant.
They were producing army field ration at the old thrift packing company over there.
And we produced millions and millions of cans of that field ration.
And I didn't know anything about pulling the vacuum or...
any of the process of canning, but I learned it.
You know, you had to learn it.

And it was interesting, and then we pulled out a certain number of cans out of each batch and put it over there in an incubator with the temperature way up, you know, and let it incubate for so many days to make sure that the product was properly processed.
And then it was shipped out to go all over the world.
It was really a big operation as far as the number of tons of supplies that went out.
Right, right.
Before we get back to your veterinary practice and so forth, I'd like to have you comment just a little bit on the demise of the Fort Worth Stockyards.
That was something that had to come, isn't that correct, because of the
The fact that it shipped the animals in when it was easier to put the packing house out near the animals, isn't that more or less the basis of the situation?
That's true of the packing plants.
Now, Armour and Swift were big operations here at that time, as we saw it.
Each plant had about 3,000 to 4,000 people working in it.
There were 3,000 to 4,000 people in each plant.
And it had got to the point, though, where a lot of their equipment was obsolete.
And these more modern plants could do the job quicker and more efficiently.
But Armour and Swift or someone could have come in here and taken over and put in one of those streamlined plants.
But the distribution of cattle chains, we saw so many of these auction markets spring up, and cattle were marketed through the auction markets, and then they'd be sent to packers.
They didn't have to come through Fort Worth.
They'd be sent to packers all over the country and even out of state.
on the fat cattle.
And of course, the stocker and feeder cattle went out to the feedlots and back to the country.
And that cut down tremendously on the heads of cattle going through the Fort Worth stockyards.
That's what really hurt the stockyards more than anything else, or your auction markets springing up.
And it was justified.
You know, if you take your cattle to an auction, you can sit there and watch them, and if you don't like the price, you can peel them.

But so many times you've shipped cattle into Fort Worth, and you've spent a lot of money getting them in here, and you'll take a bigger loss and just let them go than you would if you were closer to home with them.
And the so-called commission people got their commission no matter what.
They did, and some of them in an unscrupulous manner, unfortunately.
That didn't help the stockyards either.
You know, there was wire working in that commission business.
We had honest commission people, but we had a lot of the kind that we don't want to do business with.
I want to get off into practice now, but I think I want to.
Okay, tell us about the beginning of practice.

I know it wasn't quite the same getting out of school and so forth as if you hadn't had the three months down there in San Antonio, but when you got out on your own there in East Texas, how did you feel?
What did you do?
After I talked with you this morning, I hadn't.

really surveyed that thing so much uh in the past i just think about the changes that have been made but as i think back of the things that i didn't have the tools that i didn't have to practice with then that we have today it scares me i don't know why anybody would go into practice uh what we didn't know any better you know back there in those days uh i made a
A few little notations here.
You were more or less more out in the boonies than you were in Houghton City.
Tell us about practice out there.
You're a little closer to the soil out there than you are here.
Well, practice was rough back in those days.

you might go out and treat a milk fever for four or five dollars and pull a calf for six or eight and castrate a colt for two dollars because that was the going price in that area for the we had a lot of uh of non-graduates you know a lot of quacks in the area in fact i remember about 1940 when uh
The investigator for the state association, no, let me see.
Yeah, he was with the state association.
It wasn't the board that he was with.
He was with the state association.
And we had an old quack down there.
Did you remember the name of this investigator or not?
No, I don't remember his name.
Okay, all right.
We had an old gentleman down there that was a non-graduate.

uh and didn't even have a non-graduate license he was just right quack and he had raised a family there in carroll and he knew the justice of the peace and he was he was a good citizen and he was uh everybody knew him you know and this investigator came in and he said well we've got all the facts on this fella and uh we've got information that
with the old practice act we had then, we can get an injunction against him doing any more work.
What do you want to do?
And I thought about it a few minutes, and I said, I don't want to do it.
I said, if he can out-quack me, he can have it.
Well, he went back and told the old justice of the peace what remarks I'd made,
Well, that old man was immediately my friend, and the word spread all over the country that that doctor didn't want to do anything to that old man.
The word got around.
But anyway...
Didn't you feel that you actually did better with his goodwill and the difficult work he would just refer to you more or less?
Isn't that the way it worked out?
The way it worked out, I had the goodwill of everybody, see?
And he had a lot of friends.
He'd been down there 50 years, and he had a lot, you know, friends.
You meet a lot of people, but old friends, that's different.
And had I had him stop, it wouldn't have helped me a bit.
Sure wouldn't.
Well, actually, they weren't around too much longer.
In my case, we had one the same way in the town, and when he
Now his granddaughters are some of my excellent clients.
Yeah, right, right, right.
He borrowed a bottle of rabies vaccine from me and never paid me back.
How did you find practice?
You were talking about, I know you're getting your notes out about what you did.
The first farm calls that you made with the drugs and the equipment that you had, how did you just get the job done?
What kind of a card did you have to go out with and so forth?
Well, I had a...
I had a Ford Coupe, we called it back there then, a business cube.
And, uh... You have a bag and... Oh, yes.
And a box, too?
Yes, I still have the old bag that my sister and brother-in-law gave me when I started in practice.
Didn't you get it, uh, bronze?
No, I... All right, all right, but she still got it.
But anyway, we had calcium gluconate, uh...
You already had calcium gluconate by that time.
Yes.
Things have come a long ways.
Just within the past few years, they had found out the use, the value of calcium gluconate in milk pavers.
We still had a full of aricoline for...

orichalene and atropine uh or colics you know uh we used we had we had uh nux vomica strychnine those the same thing which we used quite a lot in bovine practice and we had some of those old barium chloride tablets uh
I believe it was barium chloride.
We called them rumen stimulants that we'd give those old cows.
As I look at what we have today that we didn't have then, I don't know how we got along, really.
Of course, your advice on husbandry and care and your knowledge of parasitism and so forth was such that you gave a lot of advice on how to
get along without a lot of medications.
Well, that's very true.
That's very true.
We gave a lot of thought even back there then to animal health and preventative medicine.
But when I started into practice, all of the vitamins, they weren't standardized.
When I was a student, when I was a student in A&M, I worked in the animal science department with graduate students studying deficiencies of vitamins.
We'd produce vitamin A deficiency in chickens, and we'd bear a bear in pigeons, I guess.
All of these deficiencies we could exhibit, we could show, and then put them on cod liver oil supplements or the vitamin C. Well, the vitamin C would use orange juice back then, see?
And nurse these animals back.
And it was very interesting, just as a student, to see
how those animals would recover if we hadn't let them go too far with deficiency.
And we'd get a vitamin E deficiency in rats by feeding polished rice, I think.
I don't know.
But anyway, we didn't have any units.
No standardization in our vitamins.
But it was good.
to know that we needed all of those necessary things.
But anyway, I think even back there then that our basic knowledge in pathology and physiology and all, we were able to...
could help a lot of people with animal health problems or by disease prevention.
Very good.
At that time, there was so much demand for veterinary medicine that there really wasn't a whole lot of crowding and so forth, was there?
No, there wasn't, but
The economy of the times forced us to work pretty hard for a little money, see?
The fees weren't anything like what they are today.
We were just coming out of the Depression, or we were still in a depressed state, and

uh... we had to work uh... our services uh... well they weren't worth a whole lot based on the economics of the animal you know right about your time was when we started the birth of what you might call aseptic veterinary medicine people like bill armistead he was in your class was he not there were several famous people in your class besides bill dan roberts
and Cocky Hander, and Darrell Sprott, who was killed in an automobile accident several years ago, who did some good work in the Philippines during the war.
He was, Sprott was very active in the quarter horse business, owned a famous quarter horse from the King Ranch, and had he lived, I'm sure that he would have been very
active in the quarter horse business today.
Well, let's see.
And George Thomas from over there.
A couple of boys from Mississippi, brothers.
One of them was a state veterinarian down there for a while.
Yeah, we had some.
Oh, my.
I can't think of those boys' names.
We had some fine people in that class.
Back in those days, we just started out on aseptic veterinary medicine.
When you first started to practice, aseptic techniques weren't really so popular then as they were a couple years later.
Isn't that right?
I think...
I think that they began stressing aseptic techniques more after my graduation, yes.
Let me put it another way.
They began to really realize the importance of it.
When I graduated from school a few years later, they wouldn't have thought of going into the abdomen of a horse.
And if they did, they gave a very unfavorable prognosis.
But now they do it with impunity.
You don't need to worry about it.
This is an interesting point.
And that came up in our lifetime, isn't that correct?
That came up in our lifetime.
We were taught that if you invaded the abdominal cavity of the horse, peritonitis was inevitable.
Do you know what?
After the war, in the...
I guess about 1947, I did the first successful cesarean on a mare.
Recorded success, recorded.
And it wasn't anything, I wasn't, it wasn't because of me, it was, I just happened to be at the right place at the right time.
I had a thoroughbred mare brought in to me that was bred to a famous
imported horse, Knight's Caprice.
He was supposed to be an outstanding horse.
He never did.
But anyway, this old boy said, I want to save that colt, even if we have to sacrifice the mother.
Well, that old mare went into labor on a Sunday afternoon, and that colt was all turned around.
I says, I don't think I'll ever deliver that colt alive.
I hit her with mag chloral and knocked her down, sliced her flank open, removed, took out that live coat, and I said, I can't let this mare die.
But then we had some sulfur drugs, and we had a few things, and I sewed her back up, and she lived.
Without shaving and all that sort of thing?
Oh, I shaved.
I'm sure.
I don't remember the details, but yeah, yeah.
But you did a reasonably septic job, right?
Yes, yes, yes.
But the thing of it is, that stimulated other people.
They said, well, look there, if that old country boy saved this mayor, well, necessarily, and that means that we can do more research in that area.
And this was recorded in the old Gen Sal Journal.
And I used to have one, but I've lost it somewhere in the long run.
But I gave all of the procedures.
John Wilkins, do you remember John Wilkins?
Well, no.
Go ahead.
John was with Gensow, and he said, Dan, we ought to write that up.
I said, yeah, all right.
So I sat down and scribbled a few notes, and he put it together, and it
And it was published in the Gen Sal Journal in about 1947, I guess.
And let me see.
Yeah, it was 46 or 47.
And as I say, it wasn't because I was
an outstanding individual in any way.
It just happened that way, see.
That's wonderful.
That was a wonderful beginning, and things went on from there.
Same way with when you moved here to Haltom City, you didn't practice too long out in East Texas, did you?
No.
You stayed in Fort Worth after you left the service.
Well, when I, let me see, in 45, when we saw the war was going to be over,
Eddie Grist was state veterinarian and his office was over here in the W.T.
Wagner building in Fort Worth.
Eddie was hired by A&M
